id="post-2642" class="post-2642 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-transportation tag-belgium tag-energy tag-power tag-solar tag-train tag-transit"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2010/10/29/solar-energy-to-power-trains/" title="Permalink to Solar Energy to Power Trains" rel="bookmark">Solar Energy to Power Trains</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2010/10/29 12:43 pm"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2010/10/29/solar-energy-to-power-trains/" title="Solar Energy to Power Trains" rel="bookmark">2010/10/29 12:43 pm</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>Trains are a great transit solution and are efficient at moving people and goods. Trains are really a green way to travel.</p><p>In Belgium, they are taking this green form of travelling and making it even better by powering the trains using solar power.</p><blockquote><p>More than 16,000 solar panels will be installed on the roof of the high-speed rail tunnel stretching just over 2 miles long. The tunnel is primarily used by the high-speed train connecting Amsterdam and Paris via Brussels.</p><p>The roof’s total surface area is 50,000 m2, roughly equivalent to 8 football fields. The installation should generate an estimated 3.3 MWh of electricity per year.</p><p>The installation commenced this summer on the tunnel’s northern side. Project completion is scheduled for December 2010. The total investment budget is $20.1 million.</p><p>Infrabel, the Belgian railway infrastructure manager, will use the green energy in the Antwerp North-South junction (including Antwerp Central Station) and to power both conventional and high-speed trains running on the Amsterdam-Brussels-Paris line. With this project Infrabel has re-emphasized its belief in renewable energy as a viable alternative, and complement, to conventional energy sources.</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://www.enfinitycorp.com/media-center/news-releases/infrabel">Read the full press release.</a></p><div
class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-1111807-2642-5385354d4ea6a' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/#blog_id=1111807&amp;post_id=2642&amp;origin=www.thingsaregood.com&amp;obj_id=1111807-2642-5385354d4ea6a' data-name='like-post-frame-1111807-2642-5385354d4ea6a'><h3 class='sd-title'>Like this:</h3><div
